import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const blogContent = `
<p>The Directed Hamiltonian Torus Decomposition problem, proposed by Knuth in early 2026, investigates whether a three-dimensional toroidal grid can be partitioned into three Hamiltonian cycles, each corresponding to a distinct edge color. While constructions for all odd grid sizes and even sizes $m \ge 8$ have been established, the $m=4$ and $m=6$ cases remained open until recently. We successfully identified valid decompositions for both cases, verified by the Lean 4 kernel.</p>

<p>This post details the engineering methodology utilized to navigate a search space of approximately $6^{215} \approx 10^{167}$ states and the subsequent formal verification process.</p>

<h2>Constraint Modeling and Hub-and-Spoke Orchestration</h2>

<p>To address this problem, we utilized a Hub-and-Spoke architecture. The central Architect hub decomposed the problem into two primary components: a high-throughput <strong>Heuristic Search Spoke</strong> and a rigorous <strong>Formal Verification Spoke</strong>.</p>

<p>The Heuristic Spoke employs Simulated Annealing (SA) to minimize an energy function representing violations of the Hamiltonian property. A critical challenge was the computational complexity of the energy evaluation.</p>

<h2>Energy Function Optimization: $O(N) \to O(1)$</h2>

<p>A naive energy evaluation requires a full traversal of all color subgraphs to verify Hamiltonian properties, resulting in $O(m^3)$ complexity per mutation. For $m=6$ (216 vertices), this overhead significantly limits search throughput.</p>

<p>The refined energy function $E(\sigma)$ accounts for both connectivity and degree constraints:</p>

<pre><code>E(σ) = Σ (components_c - 1) + Σ (vertices with in-degree ≠ 1)</code></pre>

<p>This function reaches zero if and only if each color subgraph is a single Hamiltonian cycle. To optimize performance, we implemented an incremental update mechanism. Each mutation (a local permutation change at a single vertex) triggers an $O(1)$ update to in-degree counts and a localized re-evaluation of connected components. This incremental approach achieved a $12\times$ increase in iteration frequency compared to full recomputation.</p>

<table>
<thead>
<tr><th>Case</th><th>Evaluation Method</th><th>Time to Solution (seconds)</th></tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>$m=4$</td><td>Baseline (Full Recompute)</td><td>93.0</td></tr>
<tr><td>$m=4$</td><td>Incremental (Delta Update)</td><td>3.1</td></tr>
<tr><td>$m=6$</td><td>Incremental (Delta Update)</td><td>99.5</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<h2>Non-Monotonic Cooling Schedules</h2>

<p>The energy landscape for torus decomposition is characterized by deep local minima. Standard exponential cooling often stalls when two colors achieve Hamiltonian states while the third remains fragmented. To overcome this, we implemented a non-monotonic schedule that triggers a "reheat" phase upon detecting energy stagnation. The reheat magnitude is proportional to the current best energy, facilitating escape from local optima without discarding progress toward global convergence.</p>

<h2>Formal Verification via the Lean 4 Spoke</h2>

<p>In accordance with our neuro-symbolic approach, the Heuristic Spoke acts as an oracle, providing a witness that is then independently verified by the <strong>Verification Spoke</strong>. This separation ensures that the validity of the proof is independent of the search implementation.</p>

<p>The Lean 4 kernel verifies the witness by checking pairwise injectivity and orbital properties for each color subgraph. For the $m=6$ case, the kernel performs 46,656 comparisons. This process required increasing the <code>maxHeartbeats</code> limit to $4 \times 10^8$, with verification completing in 57 seconds on an Apple M4 processor.</p>

<h2>Conclusion</h2>

<p>The successful decomposition of the $m=4$ and $m=6$ tori demonstrates the efficacy of combining high-performance heuristic search with formal verification. By optimizing energy evaluation throughput and utilizing a Hub-and-Spoke model for architectural separation, we can solve combinatorial problems that are otherwise computationally intractable.</p>

<hr>

<p><em>The formal paper is available as a
<a href="https://github.com/bneb/perqed/blob/main/projects/torus-decomposition/paper/torus_decomposition.pdf">PDF</a>.
The SA engine and Lean 4 proofs are accessible in the project repository.</em></p>
`;
